  "prompt": "My iPhone screen broke I have iCloud, would notifications I received transfer over to a replacement or would contacts transfer and notifications gone?",
  "response": "When you get a replacement iPhone and set it up using your iCloud account, most of your data, including contacts, messages, photos, and app data, should transfer over to the new device. Here\u2019s how it breaks down:\n\n1. **Contacts**: Your contacts are stored in iCloud if you have iCloud Contacts enabled. They will sync to your new device as soon as you log in with your Apple ID and enable iCloud Contacts.\n\n2. **Notifications**: Notifications are related to your apps and are not stored in iCloud. Therefore, any notifications you received on your broken iPhone will not transfer to the new device. Notifications are tied to real-time events and actions; they do not persist once the app is closed or the device is reset.\n\n3. **Other Data**: Depending on your settings, other data like photos, notes, and app data can also transfer over if synced with iCloud.\n\nTo ensure a smooth transfer, you might want to back up your old iPhone (if possible) to iCloud or iTunes before getting the replacement. This will help ensure that you have the most recent data available for your new device.",
